node.text:
@ranaabdelhamid here taking over this page after years of giggling over @yesimhotinthis’s comic strips and book with my baby sister and I’m feeling so blessed 🎉 

I’m a community organizer, facilitator and self defense trainer from Queens, NY. I run a grassroots nonprofit called Malikah (@wearemalikah) which is a joy-based training school for BIPOC women. We do self-defense, healing justice, financial
literacy and organizing training. I also organize in my working class Queens neighborhood. The work I get to do is so beautiful! Alhamdulilah. 

I’ll be sharing all things organizing, justice and self-defense throughout the day. To start, here’s a clip of my @ted talk from last year. Let me know if anything resonates in the comments below and I’m excited to get to know some of you today ☺️🎉✊🏽 and feel free to follow my journey beyond today at @ranaabdelhamid and @wearemalikah

node.text:
Eid Al-Adha is this Tuesday and during this time of year millions of Muslims perform the Hajj (the holy pilgrimage). Another special part of this day is that it requires every Muslim family to sacrifice an animal (sheep, cow, goat, or camel) and distribute the meat among the poor and needy.

Nowadays, most Muslims pay organizations to purchase the animal, perform the sacrifice, and distribute the meat. But back in the day, my parents (and most other Muslim families) would purchase the animal themselves, take them to certified butchers, and...well, you get the rest.

Did my father let me and my sisters get close to a cute wittle sheep? Yes.

Were we confused when he dropped us off at the babysitter and came back with bags of meat but sans sheep? Also yes 🤣
